   =20
 =20

Ahahaha   oops:

Lyft Inc. issued a massive correction to its outlook for earnings margin in=
 2024, saying its margin is expected to expand by 50 basis points =E2=80=94=
 not the 500 basis points written into an earnings presentation released ea=
rlier on Tuesday.
=E2=80=9CThis is actually a correction from the press release,=E2=80=9D Eri=
n Brewer, Lyft=E2=80=99s chief financial officer, said in a call with analy=
sts. =E2=80=9CIn my prepared remarks, I referenced 50 basis points of margi=
n expansion.=E2=80=9D A spokesperson for the company attributed the correct=
ion to a clerical error.
The blowout forecast may have contributed to a surge in Lyft=E2=80=99s shar=
es in after-market trading on Tuesday. The stock jumped as much as 67% on t=
he company=E2=80=99s outlooks before erasing gains during the call with inv=
estors. It was up 20% at 5:52 p.m. in New York.

Here=E2=80=99s the earnings release, predicting =E2=80=9CAdjusted EBITDA ma=
rgin expansion (calculated as a percentage of Gross Bookings) of approximat=
ely 500 basis points year-over-year=E2=80=9D in 2024. That=C2=A0500 was sup=
posed to be 50. Ah well.=C2=A0
That earnings release=C2=A0went out at about 4:06 p.m. New York time yester=
day; the  earnings call was at 4:30; a  corrected press release came out at=
 about 5:51 p.m.
  [1]
=C2=A0It is customary to do these things after market hours for =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0well, not exactly for this reason, but kind of for this reason? You p=
ut out the press release just after the market=E2=80=99s regular trading se=
ssion=C2=A0closes at 4 p.m., and investors have 17.5 hours to think about i=
t before the market opens again at 9:30 a.m. the next day. They can ponder =
the earnings release at their leisure, update their models,=C2=A0ask=C2=A0q=
uestions on the earnings call, and generally take their time to digest the =
new information and formulate a price view=C2=A0before the market opens and=
 they have to trade on it. If there=E2=80=99s anything ambiguous or surpris=
ing in the earnings release =E2=80=94=C2=A0or a typo! =E2=80=94=C2=A0the co=
mpany and the investors have time to clarify it, and they can trade the nex=
t day with well informed views.
Except that they=C2=A0can also trade after hours,=C2=A0and they sure did he=
re.  Nasdaq reported=C2=A0that Lyft was the most active stock in after-hour=
s trading yesterday.=C2=A0Bloomberg tells me that 45 million shares ($713 m=
illion worth) traded after the earnings release, roughly three times as man=
y shares as Lyft usually trades in a day.
  [2]
=C2=A0The stock closed yesterday at $12.13,=C2=A0finished the after-hours s=
ession at about $14.05 and=C2=A0opened today at $14.98. (It was trading hig=
her at noon.)=C2=A0After the press release, but before the correction on th=
e call, it got as high as $20.25. Some 21 million shares traded at prices a=
bove $15; 1 million traded at prices above $20. If you bought a million sha=
res=C2=A0at $20 when it was worth $15, because of a typo, you might be, you=
 know, $5 million worth of aggrieved. If you bought 21 million shares at in=
correct prices because of a typo, you=E2=80=99d be tens of millions of doll=
ars of aggrieved.
  [3]

Would you sue? Mehhhh. =E2=80=9CEverything is securities fraud,=E2=80=9D I =
like to say around here, but I am exaggerating. By =E2=80=9Ceverything is s=
ecurities fraud,=E2=80=9D I mean that various nontraditional things =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0sexual harassment,  mistreatment of animals,   pollution,   bad pa=
sswords =E2=80=94=C2=A0are sometimes treated as securities fraud. And   tha=
t=E2=80=99s weird: The core of =E2=80=9Csecurities fraud=E2=80=9D is, surel=
y, tricking people into buying your stock by lying about your financial res=
ults or prospects; it is a troubling and creative expansion of the law to t=
reat   defective aircraft doors as a fraud on=C2=A0shareholders.=C2=A0
Meanwhile, traditional securities fraud has been around for a long time, lo=
ng enough that lawmakers decided it didn=E2=80=99t make sense for companies=
 to get sued for every minor mistake they make about their financial result=
s or prospects, and so there are limits on what counts as traditional secur=
ities fraud. US securities law explicitly allows companies to be wrong abou=
t their earnings forecasts: There=C2=A0is a  =E2=80=9Csafe harbor=E2=80=9D =
for =E2=80=9Cforward-looking statements,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0so if you predict th=
at your Ebitda margin will expand by 500 basis points in 2024, but it actua=
lly expands by only 50 basis points, your shareholders can=E2=80=99t sue yo=
u.
There is an exception if you had =E2=80=9Cactual knowledge=E2=80=9D that th=
e statement is false.=C2=A0Did Lyft? On the one hand, presumably the execut=
ives who approved this earnings release knew that they don=E2=80=99t expect=
 margins to expand by 500 basis points. On the other hand, presumably they =
didn=E2=80=99t notice the typo. I think they=E2=80=99re fine.
Also, though, they did the right thing here!=C2=A0They put the press releas=
e out after the market closed, and they corrected it quickly and publicly b=
efore the market opened again.=C2=A0That=E2=80=99s kind of best practices f=
or a public company, and also the best they can do.   Bloomberg News report=
s:
=E2=80=9CLyft clearly did one thing right =E2=80=93 it corrected the error =
quickly and decisively,=E2=80=9D said Brad Foster, a partner specializing i=
n securities litigation at corporate law firm Haynes Boone. =E2=80=9CThe re=
ality is that people make mistakes, and mistakes are not securities fraud.=
=E2=80=9D
Well, sometimes they are, but not like this. Lyft can=E2=80=99t stop its sh=
areholders from trading after hours, but in some rough sense that=E2=80=99s=
 not its=C2=A0responsibility. If you want to trade in the after-hours marke=
t the second the press release hits the tape,=C2=A0the risk of typos is on =
you.

