      ESG as a low-interest-rates phenomenon
   =20
 =20

I   wrote last month that ESG =E2=80=94=C2=A0environmental, social and gove=
rnance investing =E2=80=94=C2=A0might have been a low-interest-rates phenom=
enon. When interest rates are zero, discount rates are low, and in some sen=
se what happens in 2050 is as important as what happens tomorrow. If a comp=
any=E2=80=99s 2050 profits are as important as its 2024 profits, then it sh=
ould spend a lot of time imagining the world in 2050, trying to make that w=
orld better and positioning itself to be profitable in 2050. Reducing green=
house gas emissions now costs money now, but it might make you more profita=
ble in 2050, and it=E2=80=99s perfectly sensible to trade $1 of profits now=
 for $2 of profits in 2050.
  [4]

And then interest rates went up and now companies just want profits next qu=
arter and care less about what happens in 2050, and so ESG has become a lot=
 less popular not only among politicians but also among companies and share=
holders. Here is a Wall Street Journal article titled =E2=80=9CAmerica=E2=
=80=99s ESG Hiring Boom Is Starting to Cool=E2=80=9D:=C2=A0

Companies are reconsidering the priority given to ESG programs and their pu=
rsuit of top ESG scores in response to pressure from investors seeking fast=
er returns on investments, [executive search firm employee Joe] Dubbin said=
. =E2=80=9CIn delivering meaningful environmental and carbon-reduction prog=
rams, the financial returns are a long way away,=E2=80=9D he said, adding e=
nergy transitions are necessary. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s not gone away. It=E2=
=80=99s just having a repricing and that=E2=80=99s driving hiring trends.=
=E2=80=9D
Some CFOs are devoting more resources to the areas of the business generati=
ng those higher short-term returns, resulting in a smaller ESG team or peop=
le incorporating ESG into their roles in lieu of positions wholly devoted t=
o it.=C2=A0

If ESG=C2=A0is =E2=80=9Chaving a repricing,=E2=80=9D is that good or bad? W=
ell, if your view of ESG investing was that it was essentially=C2=A0altruis=
tic, then you will be annoyed that investors pretended to care about the Ea=
rth a few years ago and now care only about the bottom line.
But to be fair, the investors never really said that. The explicit pitch=C2=
=A0for ESG investing has always been that ESG-focused investors want to=C2=
=A0maximize long-term returns, and they consider ESG factors as part of the=
ir value-maximizing investing process. =E2=80=9CClimate change will cause t=
he world to phase out fossil fuels, so we want to limit our fossil-fuel inv=
estments=C2=A0and buy companies that are ready for that transition,=E2=80=
=9D is the typical argument. Lots of people never=C2=A0believed=C2=A0that, =
and there are tedious fights in which US   Republican politicians claim tha=
t woke ESG investors are imposing their values on companies, while the   in=
vestors say =E2=80=9Cno we are just acting as responsible fiduciaries.=E2=
=80=9D But the investors have always said that they considered ESG factors =
as a way to maximize returns.
And=C2=A0if that were true, then what you would expect is that the investor=
s would have some field in their model for like =E2=80=9Cwill this company =
do well in the green energy transition,=E2=80=9D and the model would ascrib=
e some value to that field, and=C2=A0that value would depend on the discoun=
t=C2=A0rate. And as rates go up, the value goes down, and ESG investors who=
 truly use ESG to maximize value would care less about climate change=C2=A0=
and more about short-term value. And that=E2=80=99s=C2=A0what happened. The=
 proof that ESG is driven by investment reasons rather than wokeness is tha=
t it is repricing due to interest rates.
  [5]

That=E2=80=99s bad news for the ESG hiring boom, though   here=E2=80=99s so=
me good news from Bloomberg: =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s a renewed urgency amo=
ng investors to work out the implications [of Scope 3 emissions] for the co=
mpanies they invest in =E2=80=94 as well as their own climate commitments.=
=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CScope 3 emissions are those produced by a company=E2=80=
=99s customers and supply chain,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cintegrating Scope 3 =
data with portfolio analysis and investment decisions is =E2=80=98often hob=
bled=E2=80=99 by the complexity of Scope 3 accounting.=E2=80=9D That is bad=
 news if you are an investor looking to use Scope 3 data in your investment=
 decisions, but I guess it=E2=80=99s good news if you are an ESG profession=
al looking for a job. In financial services, complexity is good for busines=
s.

