      Prop bets
   =20
 =20

Yesterday   I wrote about dumb sports and sports-adjacent proposition bets,=
 and their susceptibility to manipulation, and people emailed me lots of ex=
amples that I found amusing and now want to share with you:
=09The players who win the Super Bowl traditionally dump Gatorade on their =
coach. This is televised, and there is an annual betting market on the colo=
r of the Gatorade. =E2=80=9CSuspicious betting leads to questions about Sup=
er Bowl Gatorade color odds,=E2=80=9D is the terrific headline of  this New=
 York Post story from yesterday: A lot of people bet on purple in the day o=
r two before the game, and then it was purple, raising questions about insi=
der betting or manipulation. =E2=80=9CWhether it was insider trading given =
by a select few on the sidelines is unknown, but the days of this popular m=
arket could be numbered.=E2=80=9D I wonder if the 49ers had different-color=
ed Gatorade ready to go, and if you had to pick the winner of the game to g=
et this market right?=09Maybe the  most famous case of prop bet market mani=
pulation came when Sutton United played Arsenal on television in the FA Cup=
 in 2017, and a UK sportsbook offered =E2=80=9Codds of 8-1 that [Sutton Uni=
ted] substitute goalkeeper Wayne Shaw would finish an entire pie while the =
game was going on.=E2=80=9D He did do that thing, and was fined=C2=A0=C2=A3=
375 and suspended for two months. =E2=80=9CPiegate,=E2=80=9D it was called.=
=C2=A0=09We talked about a guy on TikTok who pretended that he was the stre=
aker at this year=E2=80=99s Super Bowl, though he was pretty clearly joking=
. Apparently this is an old gag;  here=E2=80=99s a guy who streaked at the =
Super Bowl in 2021 and then claimed that he had bet $50,000 that there woul=
d be a streaker. No one believed him:=C2=A0=E2=80=9CNo book in their right =
mind would take $50K limits on that. Nowhere close,=E2=80=9D said a sportsb=
ook. If you want to bet $100 that there will be a streaker at the Super Bow=
l, a sportsbook will take your action. If you want to bet $50,000 that ther=
e will be=C2=A0a streaker at the Super Bowl, that sportsbook knows full wel=
l that you=C2=A0are planning to streak at the Super Bowl, and it won=E2=80=
=99t take your money.=09In non-sports, I wrote,=C2=A0=E2=80=9COne worry tha=
t people have about prediction markets is that they will call forth events =
=E2=80=A6=C2=A0If you can bet on terrorist attacks, terrorism might become =
profitable, which is a bad outcome.=E2=80=9D A reader reminded me that the =
US Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency  did try a prediction market i=
n the early 200s, but it =E2=80=9Cwas shut down in August 2003 after multip=
le US senators condemned it as an assassination and terrorism market.=E2=80=
=9D

Also in non-sports, Jeffrey Gordon of Columbia Law School emailed me about=
=C2=A0actual=C2=A0insider trading, like the kind where executives trade the=
ir companies=E2=80=99 stocks using inside information:
The downside [of legalized insider trading] is not widening of the bid-ask =
spread because of greater presence of informed trading=C2=A0but the temptat=
ion to insiders =E2=80=94=C2=A0managers =E2=80=94=C2=A0to run the firm in a=
 way that will produce more =E2=80=9Cinformation=E2=80=9D on which they can=
 trade =E2=80=94=C2=A0e.g., by choosing a more volatile operating style or =
capital structure.=C2=A0So insider trading will reduce allocational efficie=
ncy because it distorts managerial incentives to run the firm in a value-ma=
ximizing way.=C2=A0It's the streaker point you later make brought to the co=
rporate setting.=C2=A0
Right, if you are the chief executive officer of a company and insider trad=
ing is legal, you will =E2=80=A6=C2=A0well, you=E2=80=99ll buy a ton of sto=
ck, you=E2=80=99ll put out a press release saying =E2=80=9Cour margins will=
 expand by 500 basis points next year,=E2=80=9D the stock will soar, you=E2=
=80=99ll dump the stock, you=E2=80=99ll put out another press release sayin=
g =E2=80=9Cwhoops typo.=E2=80=9D You=E2=80=99ll make the stock as volatile =
as possible, because you can make more money predicting/causing stock moves=
, and trading ahead of them, than you can from running the company well.

