<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">ESG as a low-interest-rates phenomenon</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/34349750.258392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2=
FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDEtMTgvY29pbmJhc2UtdHJhZGVzLWJlYW5pZS1iYWJpZXM_Y21waWQ9Q=
kJEMDIxNDI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0=
ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMjE0JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cBd0a07a15" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;">  wrote last month</a> that ESG =E2=80=94=C2=A0env=
ironmental, social and governance investing =E2=80=94=C2=A0might have been =
a low-interest-rates phenomenon. When interest rates are zero, discount rat=
es are low, and in some sense what happens in 2050 is as important as what =
happens tomorrow. If a company=E2=80=99s 2050 profits are as important as i=
ts 2024 profits, then it should spend a lot of time imagining the world in =
2050, trying to make that world better and positioning itself to be profita=
ble in 2050. Reducing greenhouse gas emissions now costs money now, but it =
might make you more profitable in 2050, and it=E2=80=99s perfectly sensible=
 to trade $1 of profits now for $2 of profits in 2050.<a class=3D"footnote-=
index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; di=
splay: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then interest rates went up and now compan=
ies just want profits next quarter and care less about what happens in 2050=
, and so ESG has become a lot less popular not only among politicians but a=
lso among companies and shareholders. Here is a Wall Street Journal article=
 titled =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3=
4349750.258392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9hbWVyaWNhcy1lc2ctaGly=
aW5nLWJvb20taXMtc3RhcnRpbmctdG8tY29vbC0yZGQxZTBkZT9tb2Q9aXRwX3dzaiZydT15YWh=
vbw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa0b03eb6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">America=E2=80=99s ESG Hiring=
 Boom Is Starting to Cool</a>=E2=80=9D:=C2=A0</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Companies are reconsidering the priority given=
 to ESG programs and their pursuit of top ESG scores in response to pressur=
e from investors seeking faster returns on investments, [executive search f=
irm employee Joe] Dubbin said. =E2=80=9CIn delivering meaningful environmen=
tal and carbon-reduction programs, the financial returns are a long way awa=
y,=E2=80=9D he said, adding energy transitions are necessary. =E2=80=9CIt=
=E2=80=99s not gone away. It=E2=80=99s just having a repricing and that=E2=
=80=99s driving hiring trends.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some CFOs are devoting more resources to the a=
reas of the business generating those higher short-term returns, resulting =
in a smaller ESG team or people incorporating ESG into their roles in lieu =
of positions wholly devoted to it.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If ESG=C2=A0<em>is </em>=E2=80=9Chaving a repr=
icing,=E2=80=9D is that good or bad? Well, if your view of ESG investing wa=
s that it was essentially=C2=A0<em>altruistic</em>, then you will be annoye=
d that investors pretended to care about the Earth a few years ago and now =
care only about the bottom line.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But to be fair, the investors never really sai=
d that. The <em>explicit pitch=C2=A0</em>for ESG investing has always been =
that ESG-focused investors want to=C2=A0<em>maximize long-term returns</em>=
, and they consider ESG factors as part of their value-maximizing investing=
 process. =E2=80=9CClimate change will cause the world to phase out fossil =
fuels, so we want to limit our fossil-fuel investments=C2=A0and buy compani=
es that are ready for that transition,=E2=80=9D is the typical argument. Lo=
ts of people never=C2=A0<em>believed=C2=A0</em>that, and there are tedious =
fights in which US <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/34349750.258392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLz=
IwMjQtMDEtMTcvbWFraW5nLWVzZy1hLWNyaW1lP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMTQyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJ=
nV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDIxNCZ1=
dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8065f238" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
  Republican politicians claim</a> that woke ESG investors are imposing the=
ir values on companies, while the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/34349750.258392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9=
uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDEtMTgvYmxhY2tyb2NrLXN0aWxsLWxpa2VzLWNhcGl0YWxpc20_Y2=
1waWQ9QkJEMDIxNDI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld=
3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMjE0JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cB5b3da9ab" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;">  investors say</a> =E2=80=9Cno we are just=
 acting as responsible fiduciaries.=E2=80=9D But the investors have always =
<em>said </em>that they considered ESG factors as a way to maximize returns=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And=C2=A0<em>if that were true</em>, then what=
 you would expect is that the investors would have some field in their mode=
l for like =E2=80=9Cwill this company do well in the green energy transitio=
n,=E2=80=9D and the model would ascribe some value to that field, and=C2=A0=
<em>that value would depend on the discount=C2=A0rate</em>. And as rates go=
 up, the value goes down, and ESG investors who truly use ESG to maximize v=
alue would care less about climate change=C2=A0and more about short-term va=
lue. And that=E2=80=99s=C2=A0what happened. The proof that ESG is driven by=
 investment reasons rather than wokeness is that it is repricing due to int=
erest rates.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-=
color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s bad news for the ESG hiring boo=
m, though <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34349750=
.258392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDItMTQ=
vaW52ZXN0b3JzLWFyZS1iZWluZy1mb3JjZWQtdG8td3Jlc3RsZS13aXRoLXRoZS1zY29wZS0zLW=
NvbnVuZHJ1bT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMjE0MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0b=
V9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDAyMTQmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1=
ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6695e238" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  here=E2=80=99s some good n=
ews</a> from Bloomberg: =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s a renewed urgency among in=
vestors to work out the implications [of Scope 3 emissions] for the compani=
es they invest in =E2=80=94 as well as their own climate commitments.=E2=80=
=9D =E2=80=9CScope 3 emissions are those produced by a company=E2=80=99s cu=
stomers and supply chain,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cintegrating Scope 3 data wi=
th portfolio analysis and investment decisions is =E2=80=98often hobbled=E2=
=80=99 by the complexity of Scope 3 accounting.=E2=80=9D That is bad news i=
f you are an investor looking to use Scope 3 data in your investment decisi=
ons, but I guess it=E2=80=99s good news if you are an ESG professional look=
ing for a job. In financial services, complexity is good for business.</p>
