<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also in non-sports, Jeffrey Gordon of Columbia=
 Law School emailed me about=C2=A0<em>actual=C2=A0</em>insider trading, lik=
e the kind where executives trade their companies=E2=80=99 stocks using ins=
ide information:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The downside [of legalized insider=
 trading] is not widening of the bid-ask spread because of greater presence=
 of informed trading=C2=A0but the temptation to insiders =E2=80=94=C2=A0man=
agers =E2=80=94=C2=A0to run the firm in a way that will produce more =E2=80=
=9Cinformation=E2=80=9D on which they can trade =E2=80=94=C2=A0e.g., by cho=
osing a more volatile operating style or capital structure.=C2=A0So insider=
 trading will reduce allocational efficiency because it distorts managerial=
 incentives to run the firm in a value-maximizing way.=C2=A0It's the streak=
er point you later make brought to the corporate setting.=C2=A0</p></blockq=
uote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Right, if you are the chief executive officer =
of a company and insider trading is legal, you will =E2=80=A6=C2=A0well, yo=
u=E2=80=99ll buy a ton of stock, you=E2=80=99ll put out a press release say=
ing =E2=80=9Cour margins will expand by 500 basis points next year,=E2=80=
=9D the stock will soar, you=E2=80=99ll dump the stock, you=E2=80=99ll put =
out another press release saying =E2=80=9Cwhoops typo.=E2=80=9D You=E2=80=
=99ll make the stock as volatile as possible, because you can make more mon=
ey predicting/causing stock moves, and trading ahead of them, than you can =
from running the company well.</p>
